"It is a brutal and tragic reality that in the aftermath of Hurricane Sandy, hundreds of small companies will never open again – or, at best, they will struggle to survive. And this is not simply because their offices were flooded or damaged but because their IT systems were destroyed, with all their data, business processes and critical records of their business finances and customer engagements. Interruptions caused by unforeseen disasters can extend to days, even weeks and will have a serious impact on your business and your ability to service your customers. Few organisations can afford to be out of business for a few hours, let alone three or four days. But how do we motivate non-IT managers and directors to take the lead in assessing the risks and defining the plans and solutions to protect their organisations? The traditional view that IT staff should shoulder all the responsibility for business continuity should be consigned to the trash bin, argues Gurdip Sohal of Covenco Recovery Services."
